EasyVisa Project¶

Context:¶

Business communities in the United States are facing high demand for human resources, but one of the constant challenges is identifying and attracting the right talent, which is perhaps the most important element in remaining competitive. Companies in the United States look for hard-working, talented, and qualified individuals both locally as well as abroad.

The Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) of the US permits foreign workers to come to the United States to work on either a temporary or permanent basis. The act also protects US workers against adverse impacts on their wages or working conditions by ensuring US employers' compliance with statutory requirements when they hire foreign workers to fill workforce shortages. The immigration programs are administered by the Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OFLC).

OFLC processes job certification applications for employers seeking to bring foreign workers into the United States and grants certifications in those cases where employers can demonstrate that there are not sufficient US workers available to perform the work at wages that meet or exceed the wage paid for the occupation in the area of intended employment.

Objective:¶

In FY 2016, the OFLC processed 775,979 employer applications for 1,699,957 positions for temporary and permanent labor certifications. This was a nine percent increase in the overall number of processed applications from the previous year. The process of reviewing every case is becoming a tedious task as the number of applicants is increasing every year.

The increasing number of applicants every year calls for a Machine Learning based solution that can help in shortlisting the candidates having higher chances of VISA approval. OFLC has hired your firm EasyVisa for data-driven solutions. You as a data scientist have to analyze the data provided and, with the help of a classification model:

  • Facilitate the process of visa approvals.
  • Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of the employee and the employer. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • case_id: ID of each visa application
  • continent: Information of continent the employee
  • education_of_employee: Information of education of the employee
  • has_job_experience: Does the employee has any job experience? Y= Yes; N = No
  • requires_job_training: Does the employee require any job training? Y = Yes; N = No
  • no_of_employees: Number of employees in the employer's company
  • yr_of_estab: Year in which the employer's company was established
  • region_of_employment: Information of foreign worker's intended region of employment in the US.
  • prevailing_wage: Average wage paid to similarly employed workers in a specific occupation in the area of intended employment. The purpose of the prevailing wage is to ensure that the foreign worker is not underpaid compared to other workers offering the same or similar service in the same area of employment.
  • unit_of_wage: Unit of prevailing wage. Values include Hourly, Weekly, Monthly, and Yearly.
  • full_time_position: Is the position of work full-time? Y = Full Time Position; N = Part Time Position
  • case_status: Flag indicating if the Visa was certified or denied

  • The unit of wage for most employees is yearly.
  • The position of work for most employees is full-time.
  • There are around 8,000 denied cases, and around 16,000 certified cases. The visa was certified for most employees.

  • For employees with an education level of high school, the visa status for most employees is Denied.
  • For employees with an education level of Master's, Bachelor's or Doctorate, the visa status for most employees is Certified.
  • The visa status for a higher proportion of employees who have job experience is Certified, compared to those who have no job experience.
  • For employees who have a prevailing wage of 0, the visa status for most employees is Denied. For employees with a prevailing wage greater than 0, the visa status for most employees is Certified.
  • For employees who have Hour as their unit of wage, the visa status for most employees is Denied. For employees who have Year as their unit age, the visa status for most employees is Certified.

Questions¶

1) Those with higher education may want to travel abroad for a well-paid job. Does education play a role in Visa certification?

Observations:¶

  • Case status seems to vary for different education levels, which indicates that education might play a role in case status, but to what extent education affects case status needs to be further analyzed in the models.
  • For employees who have an education level of High School, there are more Denied cases than Certified cases.
  • For employees who have an education level of Master's, Bachelor's, or Doctorate, there are more Certified cases than Denied cases.
  • As the education level increases from Bachelor's to Doctorate, the proportion of cases that are Certified seems to increase, and the proportion of cases that are Denied seems to decrease.

Building/Tuning Models¶

In [31]:
#confusion matrix and performance metrics functions

#confusion matrix function for training set
def confusion_matrix_train(X_train, y_train): #X_train and y_train are parameters
    """
    Builds and displays confusion matrix for training set with the given X_train and y_train.
    Prediction are calculated through model.
    """
    X_train_pred = model.predict(X_train) #making predictions for X_train using model
    matrix_train = confusion_matrix(y_train, X_train_pred) #building confusion matrix with y_train and X_train_pred
    sns.heatmap(matrix_train, fmt='g', annot=True) #creating heatmap for matrix/annotation labels displayed as full numbers
    plt.title('Confusion matrix - Training Set') #heatmap title
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Values') #x-axis title
    plt.ylabel('Actual Values') #y-axis title
    plt.show(); #displaying heatmap
    
def confusion_matrix_test(X_test, y_test): #X_test and y_test are parameters
    """
    Builds and displays confusion matrix for testing set with the given X_train and y_train.
    Prediction are calculated through model.
    """
    X_test_pred = model.predict(X_test) #making predictions for X_test using model
    matrix_test = confusion_matrix(y_test, X_test_pred) #building confusion matrix with y_test and X_test_pred
    sns.heatmap(matrix_test, fmt='g', annot=True) #heatmap for matrix/annotation labels displayed as full numbers
    plt.title('Confusion matrix - Testing Set') #heatmap title
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Values') #x-axis title
    plt.ylabel('Actual Values') #y-axis title
    plt.show(); #displaying heatmap
    
def calculate_metrics(X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test): #X_train, X_test, y_train and y_test are parameters
    """
    Builds a dataframe with accuracy, recall, precision, and F1 score.
    Each metric is calculated with provided X_train, X_test, y_train, and y_test, along with calculated predictions.
    """
    X_train_pred = model.predict(X_train) #making predictions for X_train using model
    X_test_pred = model.predict(X_test) #making predictions for X_test using model
    metrics = pd.DataFrame() #creating dataframe for metrics
    metrics['Group'] = ['Training', 'Testing'] #adding a column to show whether the row is training or testing
    metrics['Accuracy'] = [accuracy_score(y_train, X_train_pred), accuracy_score(y_test, X_test_pred)] #accuracy column
    metrics['Recall'] = [recall_score(y_train, X_train_pred), recall_score(y_test, X_test_pred)] #recall column
    metrics['Precision'] = [precision_score(y_train, X_train_pred), precision_score(y_test, X_test_pred)] #precision column
    metrics['F1'] = [f1_score(y_train, X_train_pred), f1_score(y_test, X_test_pred)] #f1 score column
    return metrics #displaying metrics dataframe

def retrieve_importance(X_train): #X_train is a parameter
    """
    Retrieves the feature importance for all of the columns in X_train.
    Sorts the features by their importance in descending order.
    """
    imp = pd.DataFrame(index=X_train.columns) #creating dataframe for feature importance values where index is the X_train column name
    imp['importance'] = model.feature_importances_ #uses model to gather feature importance values for the importance column
    return imp['importance'].sort_values(ascending=False) #shows dataframe with values in descending order

XGBoost - Tuned¶

In [69]:
#selecting classifier
model = XGBClassifier(random_state=1, eval_metric='logloss')

#setting options for parameter values
parameters = {'n_estimators':np.arange(50,110,25),
              'scale_pos_weight':[1,2,5],
              'learning_rate':[0.01,0.1,0.05],
              'gamma':[1,3],
              'subsample':[0.7,0.9]}

#using recall score to compare parameter combinations
score = metrics.make_scorer(recall_score)

#using X_train and y_train for Grid Search/cross-validation is set to 5
search_grid = GridSearchCV(model, parameters, scoring=score, cv=5)
search_grid = search_grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

#model is the best combination of parameters
model = search_grid.best_estimator_
#applying the parameter combination on X_train and y_train
model.fit(X_train, y_train)
xgb_model = model #saving the model to a variable for later use

Comparisons

  • The Tuned Decision Tree has decent metrics, but compared to the other models, it does not have the highest Accuracy, Recall, Precision, or F1 score. So, this might not be the best model.
  • The Tuned Bagging Classifier has the highest Recall of 1.0. The F1 score is also decent at 0.80. The Accuracy and Precision are around 0.67.
  • The Tuned Random Forest Model will not be as consistent on other data sets, because it seems to overfit slightly. The testing and training metrics are slightly different. This is not the best model.
  • The Tuned AdaBoost Model has the second highest F1 score. It also has the highest Accuracy and Precision. Compared to the other models, the Recall is lower.
  • The Tuned Gradient Boosting Model has a high Recall and decent F1 score. The Accuracy and Precision are 0.68, which is not too different from the Tuned Bagging Classifier. Compared to the Tuned Bagging Classifier, the Recall score is lower. So, the Tuned Bagging Classifier seems to perform better than this model.
  • The Tuned XGBoost Model has very similar metrics to the Tuned Bagging Classifier model.
  • The Stacking Model also has similar metrics to the Tuned Bagging Classifier model and Tuned XGBoost model.

With a Recall of 1.0, the best performing models have been narrowed down to the Tuned Bagging Classifier, the Tuned XGBoost Model, and the Stacking Model. They all have an F1 score around 0.80.

It is important to identify more employees who fit the profile for being certified. If a strong candidate is incorrectly identified as not fitting the profile, it will result in a loss of a talented individual. In order to be competetive, it is important to identify many strong candidates, and not incorrectly classify them as not strong. Therefore, Recall is more important.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

There will be lower chances of getting a visa certified if:

  • Education level is only high school
  • Prevailing wage is 0
  • Unit of wage is hourly

There will be higher chances of getting a visa certified if:

  • Prevailing wage is greater than 0
  • Candidate has job experience
  • Unit of wage is yearly
  • Education is bachelor's, master's, or doctorate (Higher education levels will have higher chances of visa certification)

Further Insights and Recommendations:

  • It is out of an applicant's control where they are from, but for the applications from Europe, there are a higher proportion that are certified compared to other continents. For the applications in South America or Oceania, the proportion of applications that are certified are smaller when compared to other continents.
  • For applications where the employees intend to work in the midwest or south region, a high proportion are certified compared to other regions of employment.
  • Asia has a very high number of applicants. There are less applications from the other continents. Encouraging or motivating applicants from other continents to apply can increase applications from other continents.
  • Encouraging more applicants who have completed doctorate to apply can increase competition.
